Compiler optimization is a process of improving the performance of a program by making it more efficient. It involves analyzing the code and making changes to improve the speed, memory usage, and other aspects of the program. Compiler optimization techniques can be divided into two main categories: static and dynamic.
Static optimization techniques are applied during the compilation process, before the program is executed. These techniques include:
1. Loop unrolling: This technique involves unrolling the loops in the code to reduce the number of iterations and improve the performance.
2. Constant folding: This technique involves replacing constant expressions with their actual values to reduce the number of operations and improve the performance.
3. Dead code elimination: This technique involves removing code that is never executed to reduce the size of the program and improve the performance.
4. Inline expansion: This technique involves replacing function calls with the actual code of the function to reduce the number of function calls and improve the performance.
Dynamic optimization techniques are applied during the execution of the program. These techniques include:
1. Just-in-time compilation: This technique involves compiling the code on-the-fly to improve the performance of the program.
2. Profile-guided optimization: This technique involves analyzing the execution profile of the program to identify the most frequently executed code and optimize it to improve the performance.
3. Runtime code generation: This technique involves generating code at runtime to improve the performance of the program.
